sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322710
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Marker construct which can be used to target tnaA in E.coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a composite part containing the positive selection marker cat (chloramphenicol resistance) and the negative selection marker sacB (lethal to host in the presence of sucrose) fused to the up and down stream sequences of tnaA, the indole-producing gene. This construct can be used in the BRIDGE protocol for targeted deletion/replacement of tnaA in E.coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Maria Kowal
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Fusion of parts from E.coli and B.subtilis as well as a designed part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We had to ensure there were no intrinsic restriction sites left between the sequences.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322922
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: cat + sacB for BRIDGE: A biobrick compatible markerless recombineering method
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
BRIDGE stands for BioBrick Recombineering In Direct Genomic Editing. It is an alternative method for inserting BioBricks into the genome by using homologous recombination instead of restriction digestion, with the added bonus of not leaving a marker behind in the product.
The first step of BRIDGE requires the deletion of existing DNA (probably a non-coding piece or a non-essential gene) to introduce a construct of two genes; one an antibiotic resistance gene cat BBa-K322210, the other sacB BBa-K322921, which prevents the host from growing on sucrose. After the first step we can select for cells which have taken up the construct by growing them on the relevant antibiotic.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French, Maria Kowal and Geraldine Avila
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: sacB BBa-K322921 Source: Bacillus subtilis 168 genomic DNA. Sequence cat BBa-K322210 Source: plasmid pTG262 (broad host range vector for Gram positive and Gram negative bacteria).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
BBa-K322210 Notes: The PCR product, P1601, was initially cloned in pSB1A2, which made it easy to confirm that the gene was active, since the transformants became chloramphenicol resistant. A considerable amount of upstream DNA was included in the hope that this would include the promoter region. In the course of the iGEM project, the same PCR product was cloned in pSB1C3 to comply with new submission rules. Since this BioBrick was originally prepared for internal use, it uses abbreviated forms of the prefix and suffix lacking the NotI sites, but is in all ways compatible with RFC10 assembly.
BBa-K322921 Note: MABEL was used to mutate an internal EcoRI site to GAGTTC (underlined). Features: coding sequence runs from 13 to 1434, RBS 1 to 3, EcoRI site mutated 211 to 216.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322705
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: It is to be used for targeting genes to this locus in BRIDGE. In the BRIDGE, with this system, the markers are removed every time you insert a new gene, so they can be used again and again indefinitely. You could essentially replace the entire genome with new genes.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Richard Edward Partridge-Hicks
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Sequence results: good PCR products have been obtained.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: sacB
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: B. subtilis levansucrase. Lethal to E. coli in presence of sucrose.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
sacB encodes the Bacillus subtilis levansucrase,which is the enzyme catalyzing hydrolysis of sucrose and synthesis of levans(high-molecular-weight fructose polymers). It is lethal to gram-negative bacteria E-coli. It works with cat as an alternative method for inserting BioBricks into the genome by using homologous recombination instead of restriction digestion, with the added bonus of not leaving a marker behind in the product.
Protocol is shown here: http://2010.igem.org/Team:Edinburgh/Project/Protocol
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Maria Kowal
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Source: Bacillus subtilis 168 genomic DNA. Sequence (from SacBPlan11June10.docx)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Note: MABEL was used to mutate an internal EcoRI site to GAGTTC (underlined). Features: coding sequence runs from 13 to 1434, RBS 1 to 3, EcoRI site mutated 211 to 216.
